{
  "doc_id": "48134",
  "text": "Autoimmune rheumatic diseases (ARDs) are a heterogeneous group of diseases resulting from immune dysregulation. With improvements in immunosuppressive treatment modalities, cardiovascular disease (CVD) has emerged as the most frequent cause leading to higher mortality in these patients [CITATION_1] . In recent years, a concerted effort has been made to improve the diagnosis and treatment of CVD in ARD patients [CITATION_2] , leading some to coin the term \"cardiorheumatology\" to describe this nascent branch of cardiology [CITATION_3] . The driving force behind CVD in ARD patients is systemic inflammation [CITATION_4] , yet, even though similar mechanisms may drive neuroinflammation and subsequent damage of the brain parenchyma [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , very little is currently known regarding the interaction between heart and brain involvement in ARD patients.",
